[1m[35m# nlnav — The Logfile Navigator (custom fork)[0m

A fork of [34m[[0mlnav[34m]([0mhttps://lnav.org[34m)[0m with added features for log analysis and security investigation.

---

[1m## Added Features[0m

[4m### Timestamp Normalization[0m

Normalize all displayed log timestamps to UTC [35m`YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS[.sss]`[0m format, regardless of the original timezone or format in the file.

| Interface | How to use |
|---|---|
| Key | Press [35m`y`[0m to toggle on/off |
| Command | [35m`:normalize-timestamps [on\|off]`[0m |
| SQL | [35m`SELECT normalize_ts('2024-03-25T10:30:00-05:00')`[0m → [35m`2024-03-25 15:30:00`[0m |

Useful when comparing logs from machines in different timezones or with mixed timestamp formats (e.g. syslog + ISO 8601 in the same file).

---

[4m### SSH Traffic Flow Map[0m

Press [35m`0`[0m to open an SSH statistics panel built from the currently loaded log files.

| Interface | How to use |
|---|---|
| Key | Press [35m`0`[0m to toggle the panel |
| Command | [35m`:ssh-stats`[0m |

The panel shows three sections:

[33m1.[0m [1m**SSH Traffic Flow Map**[0m — per-source-IP flow table with destination, outcome, authenticated user(s), and auth method (e.g. [35m`public key`[0m, [35m`SSSD (LDAP/AD)`[0m, [35m`Kerberos/GSSAPI`[0m, [35m`MFA/Duo`[0m, etc.)
[33m2.[0m [1m**SSH Event Summary**[0m — counts of accepted, failed, invalid-user, disconnected, and other event types
[33m3.[0m [1m**IP Address Frequency**[0m — all IPs extracted from logs, split into [1m**Public**[0m and [1m**Private**[0m sub-groups

Supports both BSD syslog ([35m`Mar 25 HH:MM:SS host sshd[0m[35m[[0m[35mpid]: ...`[0m) and ISO syslog ([35m`2026-03-25T13:03:20+00:00 host sshd[pid[0m[35m]:[0m[35m ...`[0m) formats.

---

[4m### IOC Highlighting ([0m[4m[35m`--ioc`[0m[4m)[0m

Flag known malicious IPs from a threat-intel file and have them highlighted in both the log view and SSH stats panel.

[35m```console[0m
[35m$ lnav --ioc /path/to/ioc.txt /var/log/auth.log[0m
[35m```[0m

The IOC file is plain text — one or more IPv4 addresses per line, [35m`#`[0m comments supported. Matching IPs are highlighted with a dark background (`#2e3440`) in the log view and in the SSH flow/IP-frequency tables.

---

[1m## What lnav Does[0m

Given a set of files or directories, [1m**lnav**[0m will:

[33m-[0m decompress as needed;
[33m-[0m detect their format;
[33m-[0m merge the files by time into a single view;
[33m-[0m tail the files, follow renames, find new files in directories;
[33m-[0m build an index of errors and warnings;
[33m-[0m pretty-print JSON-lines.

Then, in the TUI, you can:

[33m-[0m jump quickly to the previous/next error (press [35m`e`[0m/[35m`E`[0m);
[33m-[0m search using regular expressions (press [35m`/`[0m);
[33m-[0m highlight text with a regular expression ([35m`:highlight`[0m command);
[33m-[0m filter messages using regular expressions or SQLite expressions;
[33m-[0m pretty-print structured text (press [35m`P`[0m);
[33m-[0m view a histogram of messages over time (press [35m`i`[0m);
[33m-[0m analyze messages using SQLite (press [35m`;`[0m).

